                      <h3>Why is my refrigerator not cooling properly?</h3>
                    </div>

                    <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                    <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="questions">
                    <p>
                      At Same Day Appliance Repair, we understand how frustrating it can be when your refrigerator isn't cooling as it should. There are several common problems that could be causing this issue. Here are a few things to check or consider:
                    </p>

                    <ol>
                      <li><b>Fan Motor:  </b>A malfunctioning fan motor can prevent your refrigerator from cooling properly. The fan motor helps circulate cold air throughout the fridge and freezer compartments. If it’s not working, you might need an old fan replaced with a new fan.</li>
                      <li><b>Back Cover Panel: </b>Make sure the back cover panel and the cover inside the fridge are securely in place. If these covers are broken or missing, it could disrupt the airflow, which is crucial for proper cooling.</li>
                      <li><b>Water Supply Lines: </b>Check the water supply lines, especially if your refrigerator has a built-in ice maker or water dispenser. Blockages or leaks in the water supply lines can affect the refrigerator’s performance. Most ice makers are dependent on a steady supply of water to function correctly.</li>
                      <li><b>Dirty Condenser Coils: </b>Dust and debris on the condenser coils can prevent your refrigerator from cooling efficiently. Cleaning the coils with soapy water can often fix this issue.</li>
                      <li><b>Freezer Door: </b>Ensure the freezer door is closing properly. If it's not sealing correctly, it can cause cooling issues. Sometimes, simply cleaning the door seal or replacing it can make a big difference.</li>
                      <li><b>Fan Motor and Mounting Bracket:  </b>Sometimes, the fan motor needs to be replaced along with its mounting bracket. If the fan is old or damaged, installing a new fan can resolve cooling issues.</li>
                      <li><b>Back Cover:  </b>Ensure the back cover is intact and properly positioned. The back cover helps protect the internal components and aids in proper airflow.</li>
                      <li><b>Thermostat Settings: </b>Verify that your thermostat settings are correct. Sometimes, the issue can be as simple as adjusting the temperature settings.</li>
                      <li><b>New Valve:  </b>If your fridge supplies water to an ice maker or water dispenser, a faulty valve could be the culprit. Replacing it with a new valve might be necessary.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>If you've checked these common refrigerator problems and your fridge is still not cooling, it may be time to get professional help. Our skilled technicians at Same Day Appliance Repair are experienced with major brands and most refrigerators. We'll diagnose the problem and fix it promptly, so you can get back to your routine without worry.</p>
